who were not integrated into the formal economy. Using anthropometric history techniques, the book assesses how a large portion of the population was affected by piecemeal policies and flaws in the process of economic modernization and growth. It contributes to our understanding of the origins of poverty and inequality, and conveys a much-needed, long-term perspective on the living conditions of the Mexican working classes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCost and standard of livingzMexicoxHistory. 0aDietzMexicoxHistory. 0aPovertyzMexicoxHistory. 0aPublic healthzMexicoxHistory. 0aPublic welfarezMexicoxHistory. 0aStaturezMexicoxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804782852zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804782852423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804782852.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles